{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7118dbc0-0e05-479f-90f4-dbf6d3994b5d","content":"The change is straightforward. In your project file, simply **remove** (or set to `false`) the `UseVSTest` property:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why this is enough:**\n- MSTest.Sdk **3.3+** uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default**. Setting `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was opting you *out* of it.\n- Removing that property (or setting it to `false`) switches you to Microsoft.Testing.Platform automatically — no extra packages needed.\n\n**What to expect after the change:**\n| Area | Notes |\n|---|---|\n| **CLI** | `dotnet test` works the same way. |\n| **Test output** | Slightly different console output format. |\n| **VS integration** | Works in VS 17.10+. Older versions need `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` if you hit issues. |\n| **`.runsettings`** | Still supported, but some custom adapters/extensions may need Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents. |\n\nAfter the change, do a `dotnet clean && dotnet test` to verify everything passes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"83049c51-099e-4e1f-9b56-aa064a1a091e","outputTokens":363,"requestId":"0C08:3A1531:21FDE7:27CC5D:69F00535"},"id":"895fad14-684f-4c9c-bcad-db8b9aae6b4e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:54:23.607Z","parentId":"af4db26b-7287-48e3-8631-f7a8b9f29c5e"}
